  "prompt": "How is Americium classified?",
  "response": "Americium is classified as a **transuranic element** and a **member of the actinide series** in the periodic table. It is a synthetic, radioactive metal with no stable isotopes. Specifically:\n\n1. **Transuranic Element**: Americium has an atomic number greater than uranium (atomic number 92), making it one of the elements produced artificially through nuclear reactions.\n2. **Actinide Series**: It belongs to the actinide series, which consists of 15 metallic elements from actinium (atomic number 89) to lawrencium (atomic number 103).\n3. **Radioactive**: All isotopes of americium are radioactive, with **Am-241** and **Am-243** being the most common and stable isotopes.\n4. **Uses**: Americium is used in practical applications, such as in smoke detectors (Am-241) and as a neutron source in research and industrial devices.\n\nIts classification reflects its position in the periodic table, its synthetic origin, and its radioactive properties.",
